Define color variables:
Set CSS custom properties (variables) for all main colors used in the dashboard — header, footer, navigation, main content, text, and links — to enable easy theming.

Create the HTML structure:

Add a hidden checkbox input (#toggle) that will act as the dark mode switch.

Build the dashboard container with semantic elements:

<header> for the top bar, containing a title and the dark mode toggle label linked to the checkbox.

<nav> for the sidebar navigation links.

<main> for the primary content area.

<footer> for the bottom footer bar.

Style the dashboard layout:
Use CSS Grid to arrange the page into two columns (navigation and main content) and three rows (header, main, footer).
Ensure the header and footer span across both columns.

Apply default (light) theme colors:
Use the CSS variables defined earlier to style backgrounds, text colors, and links for the light mode.

Implement dark mode toggle behavior:
Use the CSS selector #toggle:checked ~ .dashboard to detect when the checkbox is checked.
When checked, override the CSS variables with dark mode colors.

Ensure dynamic theme switching:
Since the dashboard’s colors rely on CSS variables, changing those variables on toggle immediately updates the entire UI without page reload.

Test the toggle:
Confirm that clicking the “Dark Mode” label toggles the checkbox and the dashboard switches seamlessly between light and dark themes.
